segments.text: who were friends of his and they talked about things that they thought were important.
We went to a couple of plays and things of that nature.
I think that must have been the time we all stayed at the Shamrock Hotel in Houston that was near the medical center.
But it was particularly nice and a very enjoyable trip.
My wife and I went on that one time as, quote, faculty.
And I remember Bob Sackowitz showing us how to pour wine.
You pick up the wine bottle with your finger like this, and you pour the wine.
And then you turn the wine bottle and lift it up, and you don't drip the wine.
And we went to ballet and to a concert.
And it was meaningful.
Did you ever have, a few people shared with me, advisor conversations where they had not been doing their best, and some advisor got through to them in a special way.
Did you ever have anybody kind of pick you off the floor?
I don't think so.
I don't think so.

probably at times that I should have had that happen, but I don't remember anybody just, I don't remember anybody either chewing on me to do better, or the other side, I don't remember anybody saying, you know, you can do a lot better.
I don't remember much encouragement either.
You're pretty much on your own.
All right, so...
If we could get back all of the faculty, staff, counselors, and so forth that were there, are there any others that you haven't mentioned that you would like to be able to say thank you to?
Oh, goodness.
I'm sure there are.
If I probably thought back about it, I could make a much longer list.
The trouble with trying to recall something like this at this time is I would leave somebody out that I shouldn't.
I worked, when I was a senior, I was editor of the Yearbook.
And I worked with Lane Stevenson.
And I always thought Lane was a much older, more mature guy.
And I see him down there now.
He was probably just a few years older than I was.
He and I went to lunch Tuesday of this week.
Good man, good man.
But he was just starting out then, I think, and he was in the, he was the head of student publications.
Describe, haven't had anybody yet who's been the yearbook editor.
Describe what that involved.
Not surprisingly, at A&M it was different than it was at that time than any other school in America.
I'm sure that at every other, I went to a couple of workshops
for a yearbook editor's article.
And I probably learned nothing because all of the people who were in charge, who were editors, were journalism majors.
And really, at A&M, it was less a journalistic function than a management function because all of the work was done by the court.
And specifically, my outfit.
My outfit had been historically
the yearbook and outfit.
In fact, I had a friend here in town who was 10 years ahead of me, class of 59, but when he was yearbook editor, he was in that outfit.
So the editor of the yearbook had traditionally come from that outfit.
But you'd have freshmen who would do most of the work, indexing, gathering class pictures, sorting it all out.
So much of the work there was done by freshmen and the poor.
And it was a matter of
of just assembling that, making sure it was all submitted properly.
And then there were a few other pages.
We had a man who sold advertising.
I had a couple of assistant editors.
One of the guys I was smart enough, I think, to pick a guy who did have some journalistic training.
He was a photographer.
And he did a lot of picture taking for us.
So it mainly was a management exercise.
What was the process by which you were selected as the editor?
Was there a panel, a committee?
There were two or three people who applied.
And as I think we probably had to go through, Lane Stevenson probably interviewed us.
The final arbiter, the final person that had to approve your selection was Earl Rudder.
And so I got the speech that Earl gave just about everyone in those days.
It had only been about three years before that he'd had to fire an editor of the battalion, Tommy DeFrank.
So I got the talk from President Rutter about how
When you do something, don't do anything that's going to embarrass you or the university, which was good advice, excellent advice.
And that was at a time when all over the country, all the other student newspapers and organizations were trying to establish their independence.
And President Rutter was wise enough to see that this is something that you probably might be embarrassed about later on if you do something stupid.
But he had to be the final person to approve it.
And Lane Stevenson was your day-to-day?
He was the person that I more or less reported to.
Where were the offices from?
Senior, when I was a freshman, maybe through my junior year, they were just down in the basement of the YMCA.
Of the Y.
But then, certainly the senior year,
And perhaps even the junior year, I don't remember for sure, we had offices in what's now the Reed McDonald building, where the journalism department is.
In fact, the editor of the yearbook had an office over there.
And it was an excellent place sometimes to get out of the dorm and just go over and study or go over and do what you wanted to.
Let's digress on Mr. Rutter.
Go ahead.
describe physically, emotionally, describe him?
You know, I think the students at A&M at that time

probably well i'm sure we didn't have any real appreciation for what type of man he was he would about the only opportunity most students had to be around him was we'd hear him speak at various official functions and he usually was kind of a dull speaker he'd go on and on and as a result most of us just kind of tuned him out and we didn't we didn't really have much appreciation for him and probably the

The closest exposure most of us had was his dog that would run around campus, Earl, and sort of a counterpart to Reveille, because as beautiful a dog as Reveille was, here was Earl, the ugliest bulldog that ever lived.
But I, in retrospect, I think we were all dumb not to see what a remarkable man Earl Rucker was.
And if there is any one person that I think has probably catapulted A&M, jump-started us to where we are now, it's Earl Rudd.
And I think it's fitting that on campus, there's a statue of him.
Because if there's two people, he and Sol Ross, probably are the two people most prominent in developing A&M from the start.
Describe him physically in reality, and then what he seemed like.
Well, I'm not sure I can really answer that very well.
Did he seem big or small?
No, he seemed big to me.
And that's because when I was in his later years, he put on quite a bit of weight, I thought.
And I don't think he was, he was not a large man.
But he seemed heavy, he was heavy set.
But he wasn't big.
But yet he had a very commanding presence.
A very commanding presence.
I was telling some friends of mine recently that
I had an experience that was one of those things that I just, even then, I thought, well, this is pretty special, but I didn't realize how special it was.
I was in his office one time, and it may have been on this occasion when he was interviewing me, and he took a phone call.
He said, he apologized, had to take a phone call.
He came back, and he said that was CBS, and he said, they're flying me to Normandy.
to recreate the 25th anniversary of D-Day.
And he said, I was just trying to make some arrangements with them.
And me, being at that time an Aggie junior, this would have been the spring of 68, when this happened, probably about the spring of 68.
And I said, you know, I've heard,
that you did some things in the war with these, but I don't really have an idea about that.
And he proceeded to spend about 20 minutes.
I was sitting in his office, and I can still picture him getting up and going over and getting some books out in his old white bookcase along one side of the road, out by his desk.
And I see him pulling books out, and he come back and showed me things that he did.
And after that was through, I had this, I walked back to the dorm and I had this sense, you know, that was a remarkable experience.
And as time has gone on, I thought, that was a remarkable experience.
Did he describe this with any emotion?
Yeah, he didn't become emotional, but it was obvious that he was sort of enjoying it.
And my recollection of what he told me
was more personal.
His account was more personal.
It wasn't that, well, I had two armies here.
It was more a matter of, well, now, here's something that I did at this point.
And it was a first person account of it.
And I thought later, that is amazing.
This man took the time to explain something like that to me.
And over the years, I've gotten to know, become acquainted with Mrs. Rutter.
And she's a remarkable, gracious lady.
But I've always thought about the memory of that.
And I just had a tremendous respect for Mrs. Rutter.
Did you students have any nicknames for him privately?
Oh, gosh.
Yeah.
I'm not sure I can remember what, I know there was, I suspect there were probably about any nicknames.
I can't remember specific ones.
Like I'll bet he was called Earl.
Oh yeah, everybody referred to him as Earl.
Now he referred to himself sometimes as Prexy because that's what the president had been called when he was an undergraduate.
I never heard students use that for him though.
No, I don't think so.
light bulb up on top of the academic building was, in his day, called Prexy's Moon.
And in his undergraduate days, each freshman was supposed to try to shoot out Prexy's Moon at least once.
And he mentioned Prexy's Moon once to me.
I didn't know what he was talking about.
No, I didn't know about that.
All right, other characters.
What about in the Corps?
the commandant or any, were there, who was commandant in those days?
Well, I think it was,
I had to just go back and look.
I was not, I was focused on the core at that point.
What about Dean of Students?
Dean Hannigan was Dean of Students.
Did you have any interaction?
Never had any, never had any interaction with him.
All right.
Malan Sutherland was, who's now the Dean of Students.
What was his nickname?
Maybe it was fish drill team advisor.
Slink.
Slink, okay, I don't think I heard.
Wedge, do you remember him?
Simplest tool known to man, that was another one.
Where I'm headed is, do you remember any faculty nicknames that you can share?
Oh dear.
Square root Jackson, cube root Kent.
You'd never know them.
Blue book Benton.
Blue book Benton, yeah, yeah.
What was it, the guy in the business school?
Gosh, what was his name?
Oh dear.
What was his name, Screamin' Al?
Screamin' Al Nelson?
Yeah.
Jock Woods in Government, Notes Nance, Ivy Lee Taylor.
Now, were those nicknames terms of derision, or in fact terms of kind of pleasant recognition?
I think it was pleasant recognition.
OK, so he's a character, but that's all right.
Yeah.
I think that's one.
In business, when you were a business major, who was the key leader of the business program overall?
Who was the dean?
Dean Pearson.
Did you ever have any interaction with him?
I don't remember.
I may have met him once, but there wasn't all that much.
Let's go into the classroom.
How did students behave in the classroom?
They slept.
Did you all go to class regularly?
Some did, some didn't.
I think there was probably a greater premium on class attendance then than perhaps there is now.
By far.
And part of it, I think, is that in the core, you had to get up.
So if you were up, you might as well go to class.
If I were in a class where I wasn't doing well, I darn sure would go.
But no, I think there was a greater emphasis on class attendance.
And how did students dress?
Well, if you were in a corps, you wore your uniform.
What about the civilian students?
How did they dress?
Well, my recollection is they dressed fairly decently.
My daughter goes in t-shirts and jeans now, and I don't think you saw that.
I think the female students, there would be one female student sometimes in a class, and she was usually dressed fairly nicely.
And most of the civilian students were dressed in slacks or jeans sometimes, a nice sport shirt.
I think there was a, I wouldn't say more professional,
Maybe some of that was contributed to by the Corps.
Those guys were always in uniforms, and so they were always, you know, shine shoes and that sort of thing.
So that may have raised the level.
All right.
Now, the first coeds, were there coeds already there your freshman year?
I don't... What was your freshman year?
I was there in the fall of 65.
I don't remember any classes.

I might have had a class my freshman year with one girl, I don't remember, but then certainly by the time I was a junior, senior, particularly in business, in liberal arts classes, you'd frequently have one, two, three.
Some of them were wives of students, some of them were
just girls from around the area.
But yeah, it wasn't as unusual.
How did you young men treat those females?
You know, I think for the most part, my sense is that most of the time they just ignore them.
But were they rude to them?
I think some probably were, but

I'm sure that if you talked to the girls, they would tell you how all the comments, they were probably sensitive to the comments, but I think for the most part, guys just ignored them because they didn't really know what to say.
I don't remember too many situations where there was an open abuse or, you know, get out of here or anything like that.
I'm sure that happened to them and they tell you that, but I didn't witness anything like that.
One I tell on myself.
I had a class, a 1 o'clock class, on the second floor of Nagel.
And the history department office was on the west end of that hallway.
And for a few months, there was an extremely shapely part-time secretary in the history department.
And she would come after.
She had a late lunch.
And at about 1.15 to 1.20, you'd hear these high heels.
And every guy in the room.
would start staring.
And so one day, just as they were all, I went over and closed the door.
And I heard an epithet from the back of the room aimed at me.
Do you recall about what it cost when you were a student?
What did a semester or a year cost?
I'm going to say a semester was somewhere under $500 or so for everything.
I can still remember that, I can't remember exactly, tuition was $50, you know, and I'm thinking that the room and board was like $300 or something.
I may be totally off, but I can still remember that talking with my father at one time and
realizing that it was cheaper for me to go to the school at A&M and live down there than it would have been for me to live at home and go to TCU.
And did you earn any or all of that money yourself?
When I became a junior and went on contract, Army contract, I got a little pay for that.
When I was a senior, the job as editor of the yearbook was a paying position.
I got some money.
It was about $50, $75 a month for that.
But then what I'd do in the summers is I'd work like everybody else.
I went to summer school some at UTA.
Took two or three history classes out there.
Took history of England out there.
That was recommended if you thought about law school when I was thinking about it.
And so I'd work, I'd go to school and then I'd work some more, but I tried to do that so I'd have some spending money.
You didn't have a job, a full-time job?
No, no, not while I was in school.
See, once I talked to these people in the 30s and 40s, having a job, particularly in the dining hall, was the end of the rainbow to help
Let's see, do you remember any famous visitors to the campus?
Politicians, speakers, performers?
Oh yeah, I know we had them and I'm trying to think of...
They'd have some performers come, you know, and appear at G. Raleigh White.
Seems like that was about the time that they started the Skona series, and I remember they'd have some people come in for that, and I used to enjoy coming over to some of those and listen.
Probably most of my friends thought that was very stupid of me to do that, showing any interest at all in anything.
I don't think we had, we certainly didn't have anywhere near the level of outside speakers that they have now.
Let's see, then various organizations.
What happened in or around the YMCA?
What was the why?
What function did it serve?
You know, I think that was more, my sense is that was more the sort of the focal point of activity.
Many of the student organizations had offices there.
Student housing was in there, as I recall.
And they had a lot of different student organizations that would meet there, all the way from religious organizations to hometown clubs and all kinds of things like that.
As I mentioned, some of the student publications had their offices in there early on.
MSC.
What role did the MSC?
The MSC was, I think they used to say it was the living room of the campus, and I think that was exactly right.

You know, my goodness, when you got to be a freshman year, you'd go over there to try to avoid upperclassmen some, and when you got to be a junior and senior, you'd go over there between classes and sit with your buddies and drink coffee, and I can still remember that
Of course, now they've got that big dining room area in the MSC.
But back in those days, they used to have about two or three different type of coffee shops in there.
And, boy, you could just go in there and sit for an hour.
People would just come and sit down.
And then somebody would get up and leave and go to class.
Somebody else would come and sit down.
You could spend the whole morning over there if you wanted to, visiting with friends.
The barber shop was over there where you could get your hair cut.
Those guys weren't the most skilled barbers.
I'm sure about all they knew was shaving heads.
And then there were all the activities that the MSC sponsored.
Alright, Guy and Hall.
What role did it play?
Guy and Hall was used, in my recollection, mainly when they wanted to have large meetings, like class.
I think we had class meetings over there.
I don't remember, it was not used as much because when they wanted to, it was mainly a theater.
They had plays in there and things of that nature.
They weren't showing movies anymore, were they?
I don't believe they were.
I don't remember.
I don't believe they were.
Any large shows that came would play in G. Robbie White.
They still had the theaters north of campus and campus theater.
But Guyon Hall was just sort of falling into disuse as much as anything, as I remember.
Campus, either on campus or off campus religious activities, did those affect you at all?
Sure.
I come from a Baptist church here.
My first year down there, I went to church frequently.
And the First Baptist Church was right across the street from the campus.
And it's moved, but most of the other churches are still there in the same location.
And I think as much as anything, those for students were refuges from core things, if that's what they were looking for.
But I was not involved in many of the, like a lot of the kids now are involved in different student ministry activities.
I wasn't involved in that.
Let's see.
Help.
me understand the student body in general when you were there.
Basically, these students came geographically from where?
Cities, country, everywhere?
I've never thought about that specifically.
I do think that there were probably more students then from small towns than there are now.
But I think it's also true that the largest number of students came from the largest towns.
It seemed like there were more from Houston, San Antonio,
I was always amazed at A&M how many students there were from San Antonio.
It seemed like there were a huge number from San Antonio.
There weren't as many from Fort Worth in those days.
There seemed like a lot more from Dallas.
But then every time you meet someone, there are so many from small towns in East Texas and Central Texas.
And you find more from out of state, I think, too.
For some reason, I had the sense that there were more out of state students then than perhaps there are now.
But that's just anecdotal.
I don't know if that's true.
All right.
If liberal is someone receptive to change, conservative is someone hesitant to change, attitudinally, what was the student body like?
As conservative as you could get.
in terms of religious affiliation?
Were they diverse or basically Protestant?
My sense is that it was more diversity than you might think.
Probably more Protestant.
I can still remember some Jewish people who were in school when I was.
Several Catholics.
I think it was a pretty good event.
Do you remember any events which indicated anything other than respect for someone's religious... Oh, no.
No, I don't.
I think that what I do remember is a lot of people who were
For the most part, when you took males who were 19 to 21 years old, there wasn't the strongest religious devotion in any group like that.
But I never sensed any religious intolerance.
Do you remember any international students?
Yes.
There were a lot of graduate students, of course, with typical Aggie sensitivity.
Most of them lived in a dorm that was called the Black Hole of Calcutta.
But I remember there was at least a couple of Korean students in an accounting class I had.
There were a smattering of them, but I think they were mainly in graduate school.
Were there any black students?
Sure.
Oh, yeah.
Well, I say sure.
There were at least two that were in the Corps when I was.
One of them was a very good friend of mine.
Another one, I didn't know him well.
He lives in Fort Worth now.
I don't really, I still don't really know him.
This one you said was a good friend of yours, isn't it?
Bill Mayholmes.
Spell it.
M-A-H-O-M-E-S. Bill was... Because, see, those are...
I want to...
If I can, I want to try to sell the idea that I should go interview some of the first women and some of the first black students.
Because I have the impression that there were no problems with the first black students.
I don't think there were any incidents.
There weren't any demonstrations.
No demonstrations.
I think...
I think Bill...
Bill would tell you that it was not easy.
He and I had all of our classes together our freshman year.
We were both in engineering.
Both of us changed from that.
In fact, Bill was a good friend of mine.
We went to law school together.
He went on to law school with me.
And he's done very well.
But to compound his situation, he stuttered, which I admire him for.
for staying with somebody.
I wouldn't have been tough enough to make it.
But no, it had to have been very difficult because there was not the restriction
Well, upperclassmen in those days, you know, a freshman is just a piece of property.
And so there was probably no limit on what freshmen, they would feel no constraints.
Upperclassmen would feel no constraints on what they said to a freshman.
Now, was he a freshman the same way you were?
So he's among the first.
I think he probably was the first guy to ever go through four years.
See, this is another part of A&M's history that Mr.
Rudder handled well.
He called the Pentagon, without any of us knowing him,
wearing those two stars as Major General in the Reserve, and said, okay, we are going to integrate.
The board has backed me.
That hasn't publicly been announced.

When you send some of the active duty enlisted personnel, as you normally do with the Army paying the bill, this summer when you send some that are black, no problem cases, nobody's got a conduct problem or a grade problem,
And Mr. Heaton then called every faculty member and said, don't worry, when you meet class tomorrow, they have been admitted.
